   <center><h2><u>Rural Employment and Employment Schemes</u></h2></center>
   <h2>
    <u>1. MGNREGA (Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act) </u>
 <br>Objective: Provides at least 100 days of guaranteed wage employment per year to rural 
households willing to do unskilled manual work. 
 <br>Eligibility: Any rural household with adult members ready to work. 
 <br>Benefits: 
<br>Wage employment (paid directly via DBT). 
<br>Creation of durable assets like roads, ponds, wells. 
 <br>Implementation: Apply via Gram Panchayat with a job card; Panchayat allocates work.
   </h2>
   <h2>
    <u>2. DDU-GKY (Deen Dayal Upadhyaya Grameen Kaushalya Yojana) </u>
<br>Objective: Skill development and placement program for rural youth. 
 <br>Eligibility: Rural youth aged 18–35 from poor families. 
 <br>Benefits: 
<br>Free skill training in demand-driven trades. 
<br>Placement support in organized sector jobs. 
 <br>Implementation: Training through Rural Skill Centres; funded by MoRD
     </h2>
     <h2>
        <u>3. PMKVY (Pradhan Mantri Kaushal Vikas Yojana) </u>
<br>Objective: National skill certification program to empower youth with industry-relevant 
skills. 
<br>Eligibility: Indian nationals with Aadhaar; prior experience required for Recognition of 
Prior Learning (RPL). 
<br>Benefits: 
<br>Free short-term training. 
<br>Skill certification recognized by industries. 
<br>Placement assistance. 
<br>Implementation: Managed by NSDC under Ministry of Skill Development.
     </h2>
        <h2>
            <u>4. SVEP (Start-Up Village Entrepreneurship Programme) </u>
<br>Objective: Promote rural entrepreneurship and non-farm livelihoods. 
<br>Eligibility: Rural youth and women, especially SHG members. 
<br>Benefits: 
<br>Loans and training for micro-enterprises. 
<br>Business support services. 
- Implementation: Sub-scheme under NRLM; block-level projects for 4 years.
        </h2>
        <h2>
            <u>5. NRLM (National Rural Livelihood Mission) – Aajeevika</u>
            <br>Objective: Organize rural poor into Self-Help Groups (SHGs) and federations for 
sustainable livelihoods. 
<br>Eligibility: Rural poor households, especially women. 
<br>Benefits: 
<br>Access to credit and financial services. 
<br>Capacity building and livelihood support. 
<br>Implementation: Launched in 2011; covers 7 crore households across India.
        </h2>
